After receiving email invite to repositories, or teams, the user clicks on the link, and is taken to the login page.  They enter their creds, and hit login, and the page just refreshes with empty credential form fields.  If the user then tries to login directly at https://bitbucket.org/account/signin/?next=/ with the same credentials, they are able to login as normal.

*Workaround 1:* The issue only occurs when using an email address. If the invitation is sent to an existing Bitbucket user, the team can add the username directly to the team. If not, the recipient of the invitation will need to create a new Bitbucket account first so the team can add his username.

*Workaround 2:* Copy the end of the actual invitation link, and navigate to it in your browser: https://bitbucket.org/invitations/repository/{invitation_long_string}

My team mates and I use a hodge podge of operating systems and mail clients.

Occasionally the "%0D" (carraige return character) in a diff URL generated by bitbucket are stripped or mangled.

My advice is to generate DIFF links without %0D in the URL as it appears some email programs try to strip that out or can break it.

According to my research %0D is a carraige return. URLs should not need a marked up carraige return character embedded in it, just my two cents.

So, the problem is not easily reproduceable however a feature request would be to have more reliable diff links without entity references embedded in them.

Specifically by way of example it would be nice if the diff URLs were human readable: eg

{code}
https://bitbucket.org/{account}/{repo}/branches/compare/{tag2}:{tag1}#diff
{code}

instead of

{code}
https://bitbucket.org/{account}/{repo}/branches/compare/{tag2}%0D{tag1}#diff
{code}

In the mail client I use (Mac Mail), I checked a sent email in a thread and the %0D had been stripped completely, leaving a URL of this form:

{code}
https://bitbucket.org/{account}/{repo}/branches/compare/{tag2}{tag1}#diff
{code}

which generated this error message at bitbucket:

{code}
illegal spec: {tag2}{tag1}
{code}

It took quite awhile to figure out what was missing.

A workaround might be for bitbucket&#x27;s front controller to detect this and redirect, though a wide variety of string parsing options would need to be checked for two actual tag/branch on the inbound account and repo in the precedent URI segments.

We&#x27;re using Mercurial for version control. I don&#x27;t think that applies in this case but wanted to mention it.
